<paragraph id="8BDE36D83130FFE3364BFCE2FD5B508C" blockId="9.[264,1325,817,1283]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">
The 
<typeStatus id="54DA887A3130FFE33603FCE2FEAE5775" box="[320,371,817,843]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">type</typeStatus>
series of 
<taxonomicName id="4C614D5B3130FFE336ADFCE2FDAC5774" box="[494,625,817,842]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Puliciphora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cavatica">
<emphasis id="B915EACA3130FFE336ADFCE2FDAC5774" box="[494,625,817,842]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">P. cavatica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, from 
<collectingCountry id="F37676483130FFE33584FCE2FCF35775" box="[711,814,817,843]" name="Trinidad and Tobago" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">Trinidad</collectingCountry>
, comprised a series of males and a single female specimen that was badly discoloured (probably by being preserved in alcohol when still partly teneral). Since then Dr Will Reeves sent me two good female specimens from 
<collectingCountry id="F37676483130FFE3364BFC7AFEA157FD" box="[264,380,937,963]" name="Dominica" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">Dominica</collectingCountry>
(Parish of St Joseph, Springfield Estate, humid forest, 
<date id="FFDF10183130FFE33363FC7AFB2157FD" box="[1056,1276,937,963]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" value="2004-04-15" valueMax="2004-04-17" valueMin="2004-04-15">
<number id="3DA924FF3130FFE33363FC7AFBB557FD" box="[1056,1128,937,963]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" value="16.0" valueMax="17.0" valueMin="15.0">15–17</number>
April 
<number id="3DA924FF3130FFE333FFFC7AFB2157FD" box="[1212,1276,937,963]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</date>
). In addition he has sent a single, slightly teneral, female from the 
<collectingCountry id="F37676483130FFE334A8FC02FBE157D5" box="[1003,1084,977,1003]" name="United States of America" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">U.S.A.</collectingCountry>
(Alabama, Baldwin Co., Ft Morgan Rd, 
<date id="FFDF10183130FFE336B4FC2AFD6C502D" box="[503,689,1017,1043]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" value="2004-03-22">
<number id="3DA924FF3130FFE336B4FC2AFDC9502D" box="[503,532,1017,1043]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" value="22.0">22</number>
March 
<number id="3DA924FF3130FFE33532FC2AFD6C502D" box="[625,689,1017,1043]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" value="2004.0">2004</number>
</date>
). The measurements of the specimens from 
<collectingCountry id="F37676483130FFE333FAFC2AFAF0502D" box="[1209,1325,1017,1043]" name="Dominica" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">Dominica</collectingCountry>
are close to those given in the description of 
<emphasis id="B915EACA3130FFE33476FBF2FC755004" box="[821,936,1057,1082]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName id="4C614D5B3130FFE33476FBF2FC7E5004" box="[821,931,1057,1082]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Puliciphora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sobria">P. sobria</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
but the specimens have a paler thorax. The failure to recognise Borgmeier’s species stems from inaccurate depiction of tergite 
<quantity id="4C999B3D3130FFE33619FBA2FE5A50B5" box="[346,391,1137,1163]" metricMagnitude="-1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.524" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" unit="in" value="6.0">6 in</quantity>
his figure of the dorsal aspect. 
<figureCitation id="135A2A5D3130FFE335B9FBA2FC9050B5" box="[762,845,1137,1163]" captionStart="FIGURES 18 – 19" captionStartId="12.[264,383,826,850]" captionTargetBox="[507,1092,291,814]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[456,1136,266,856]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 18 – 19. Puliciphora females: (18) P. s u a v i s from above (after Borgmeier, 1960); (19) P. sobria, abdominal tergites 4 – 6. Scale bar = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/169851/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">
Fig. 
<number id="3DA924FF3130FFE33473FBA2FC9050B5" box="[816,845,1137,1163]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" value="19.0">19</number>
</figureCitation>
depicts T 
<number id="3DA924FF3130FFE33481FBA2FC0C50B5" box="[962,977,1137,1163]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" value="4.0">4</number>
–T 
<number id="3DA924FF3130FFE334B0FBA2FBDF50B5" box="[1011,1026,1137,1163]" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" value="6.0">6</number>
. The male of this species was described under 
<emphasis id="B915EACA3130FFE336BCFB4AFD5B508C" box="[511,646,1177,1202]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="48">
<taxonomicName id="4C614D5B3130FFE336BCFB4AFD5E508C" box="[511,643,1177,1202]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Puliciphora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="48" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cavatica">P. cavatica</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
